        <div class="abstract-box">
            <h2 id="section-0">Abstract</h2>
            <p>This paper presents the first spatially resolved kinematic evidence for dust in the outflows of Active Galactic Nuclei (AGN). The GATOS collaboration utilized JWST observations with NIRSpec IFU and MIRI MRS data of 10 local Seyfert galaxies to extract the kinematics of Polycyclic Aromatic Hydrocarbon (PAH) features using Principal Component Analysis (PCA) tomography.</p>
            
            <p>PAHs comprise the smallest carbonaceous dust molecules in the interstellar medium and produce infrared emission features. The authors find that PAH velocities match the molecular gas traced by H₂ rotational transitions. For NGC 5728 and NGC 7582, both disk and outflow components are present. The kinematic signatures of large, neutral PAHs (11.3 μm and 17 μm features) match the velocity field of high-ionization lines like [NeVI], confirming the presence of dust in AGN-driven outflows. However, the 6.2 μm PAH shows altered intrinsic profiles, while 3.3 μm PAH kinematics trace only the circumnuclear disk, suggesting outflow PAHs are more neutral and larger than in star-forming regions.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="section-1">Main Findings</h2>

        <h3>First Direct Detection of Dust in AGN Outflows</h3>
        <p>The most significant result is the <strong>first kinematic detection of dust molecules (PAHs) in AGN-driven outflows</strong><sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. Using the infrared emission features of large neutral PAHs (11.3 μm and 17 μm), the authors identified velocity signatures consistent with outflows in NGC 5728 and NGC 7582, directly demonstrating that AGN eject dust along with ionized and molecular gas.</p>

        <h3>PAH Velocity Matching with Molecular Gas</h3>
        <p>PAH kinematics closely match the molecular gas traced by H₂ rotational transitions<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>, indicating that dust and gas are mechanically coupled in these outflows. This coupling suggests that dust is not simply passively dragged by the outflow but responds dynamically to the same driving forces as the gas.</p>

        <h3>Outflow PAHs are Larger and More Neutral</h3>
        <p>A critical finding is that PAHs in <WikiLink slug="pages/AGN_Outflows" text="AGN outflows" /> are preferentially large (11.3 μm and 17 μm features detected) and neutral, distinct from star-forming regions where smaller PAHs (6.2 μm) are more prominent<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. This suggests:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>The extreme radiation field in AGN may selectively destroy or ionize smaller PAHs</li>
            <li>Different grain populations exist in AGN versus starburst environments</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Dust_Destruction" text="Dust destruction mechanisms" /> in AGN winds may preferentially target certain sizes</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Disk vs. Outflow Kinematic Separation</h3>
        <p>By subtracting the circumnuclear disk velocity component, the authors successfully isolated pure outflow kinematics<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. The outflow velocity field matches that of high-ionization potential ([NeVI], IP = 158 eV) tracers, suggesting outflows driven by highly energetic processes.</p>

        <h2 id="section-2">Scientific Approach: Advanced Data Analysis</h2>

        <h3>PCA Tomography: Novel Technique</h3>
        <p>The paper introduces Principal Component Analysis (PCA) tomography as a method to extract kinematic information from broad, complex PAH features<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. This approach addresses the challenge that PAH features have:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Broad intrinsic profiles difficult to decompose</li>
            <li>Variations in shape due to environmental conditions</li>
            <li>Complex blending in spatially resolved observations</li>
        </ul>
        <p>PCA tomography statistically decomposes these features to extract underlying velocity components.</p>

        <h3>Sample: GATOS Seyfert Galaxies</h3>
        <p>The study utilizes 10 local Seyfert galaxies from the GATOS survey, a major JWST program studying AGN and their impact on galaxy evolution. This large sample provides robust statistics on AGN outflow properties across diverse environments.</p>

        <h3>Complementary JWST Instruments</h3>
        <p>The combination of <strong>NIRSpec IFU</strong> (high-resolution spectroscopy, shorter wavelengths) and <strong>MIRI MRS</strong> (mid-infrared spectroscopy, PAH-rich region) provides comprehensive kinematic coverage across the AGN-driven outflow.</p>

        <h2 id="section-3">Implications for Galaxy Evolution</h2>

        <h3>AGN Feedback and Gas/Dust Coupling</h3>
        <p>The kinematic coupling between dust and gas in AGN outflows has critical implications for understanding <WikiLink slug="pages/AGN_Feedback" text="AGN feedback" /> as a mechanism for galaxy quenching. Dust removal is not incidental to gas removal—it occurs simultaneously and dynamically<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. This means:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>AGN feedback may simultaneously quench <WikiLink slug="pages/Star_Formation" text="star formation" /> and alter infrared-based diagnostics</li>
            <li>Dust properties in outflowing gas may differ from static ISM, affecting SED fitting</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Dust_Continuum_Observations" text="Dust continuum observations" /> of galaxies in outflow phases may be misleading</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Reframing AGN Outflow Composition</h3>
        <p>Previous AGN outflow studies focused on gas phases (ionized, molecular, atomic). This work reveals that <strong>dust is an integral component of outflows</strong>, not a passive byproduct. Understanding outflow composition requires accounting for:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Multiple dust grain sizes and compositions</li>
            <li>Dust destruction and sputtering processes</li>
            <li>The fate of metals and carbon in AGN-driven outflows</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>High-Redshift Galaxy Observations</h3>
        <p>The PAH features detected here (mid-infrared lines) can be observed at higher redshifts with infrared telescopes. These GATOS results provide crucial anchors for interpreting PAH kinematics in high-z AGN, helping identify which galaxies experience powerful outflows.</p>

